In article <vi1H_+bd6@cs.psu.edu>, so@fortran.cs.psu.edu (Nicol C. So) writes...
>In article <1992Mar30.190931.28623@hal.com> ess@hal.com (Eric Swildens) writes:
>>The initial publication in the ACM of the RSA algorithm and process is
>>dated in early 1978 (I think Jan or Feb).  A US patent lasts for 17
>>years.  This leads me to believe that the RSA patent should be good for
>>at most 3 more years.  Anyone want to verify this?
>Seems not.  Below is from an old article: ...
>        Inventors: Rivest, Shamir, Adleman
>        Filed: December 14, 1977
>        Granted: September 20, 1983         [Expires: September 19, 2000]

They last for 17 years from when they are issued.  You do have to apply
within one year of publication though.

Six years or more between filing and issuance are by no means unusual.

